SIMPLE: strangle
RECORDS: 2

==== ENTRY 1 ====
HEADWORD: Strangle
<hw>Stran"gle</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>v. t.</pos> <vmorph>[<pos>imp. &
p. p.</pos> <conjf>Strangled</conjf> <pr>(?)</pr>; <pos>p. pr. & vb.
n.</pos> <conjf>Strangling</conjf> <pr>(?)</pr>.]</vmorph> <ety>[OF.
<ets>estrangler</ets>, F. <ets>⟦eacute⟧trangler</ets>, L.
<ets>strangulare</ets>, Gr. <?/, <?/, fr. <?/ a halter; and perhaps akin
to E. <ets>string</ets>, n. Cf. <er>Strain</er>, <er>String</er>.]</ety>
<sn>1.</sn> <def>To compress the windpipe of (a person or animal) until
death results from stoppage of respiration; to choke to death by
compressing the throat, as with the hand or a rope.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>Our Saxon ancestors compelled the adulteress to
<qex>strangle</qex> herself.</q> <rj><qau>Ayliffe.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>To stifle, choke, or suffocate in any
manner.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>Shall I not then be stifled in the vault, . . . ⟦br⟧
And there die <qex>strangled</qex> ere my Romeo comes?</q>
<rj><qau>Shak.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>3.</sn> <def>To hinder from appearance; to stifle; to
suppress.</def> ⟦ldquo⟧<xex>Strangle</xex> such thoughts.⟦rdquo⟧
<rj><au>Shak.</au></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Strangle</ent>⟦br⟧

==== ENTRY 2 ====
HEADWORD: Strangle
<hw>Stran"gle</hw>, <pos>v. i.</pos> <def>To be strangled, or
suffocated.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Strangleable</ent>⟦br⟧
